                                <span></span>
                                <span><p>In <em class="b">&#8220;Sunny Side Up&#8217;&#8217;</em> (Hirmer), artist Eran Shakine, who lives in Tel Aviv and London, pokes fun at lofty notions about art, inspiration, and genius. In the text below his sketch of a museum scene, Shakine notes that museumgoers spend an average of 10 seconds with each work, half of which is spent reading the label. He draws a hairpiece in the shape of, say, a Frank Gehry building and plops it on Gehry&#8217;s head. He dresses Ralph Lauren and other male fashion designers in the clothing they create for women. With a few bold lines, Shakine creates a world of commentary.</p></span>
                                <span></span>
                            </DataContent>
